---
export const prerender = true;

import MainLayout from '../../layouts/MainLayout.astro';
import ZakatCalculator from '../../components/tools/ZakatCalculator';

const title = 'Zakat Calculator Pakistan 2026 — Calculate Your Zakat Online';
const description =
  'Free online Zakat calculator for Pakistan using live gold and silver prices. Supports both Silver and Gold Nisab basis, includes business inventory and receivables.';
const pageUrl = 'https://hisaabkar.pk/tools/zakat-calculator';
---

<MainLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'WebApplication',
    name: title,
    description,
    url: pageUrl,
    applicationCategory: 'FinanceApplication',
    operatingSystem: 'Web, Android, iOS',
    offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'PKR' },
    featureList: 'Live gold and silver nisab, Silver and Gold Nisab basis, Business inventory, Cash and receivables, Instant calculation',
    inLanguage: 'en-PK',
    publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'HisaabKar.pk', url: 'https://hisaabkar.pk' },
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://hisaabkar.pk' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Tools', item: 'https://hisaabkar.pk/tools' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'Zakat Calculator', item: pageUrl },
    ],
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'HowTo',
    name: 'How to Calculate Zakat in Pakistan 2026',
    description: 'Step-by-step guide to calculating your annual Zakat obligation using live gold and silver nisab rates in Pakistan.',
    totalTime: 'PT5M',
    tool: [{ '@type': 'HowToTool', name: 'HisaabKar.pk Zakat Calculator' }],
    step: [
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 1, name: 'Choose your Nisab basis', text: 'Select Gold Nisab (87.48g of 24K gold) or Silver Nisab (612.36g of silver). Most Pakistani Hanafi scholars recommend the Silver Nisab as it is lower and includes more Muslims in the obligation.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 2, name: 'Enter your cash and bank balances', text: 'Add all cash at hand, savings account balances, and fixed deposits that you have held for one complete lunar year (hawl). Do not include money borrowed or owed.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 3, name: 'Enter your gold and silver holdings', text: 'Enter the weight in grams or tolas of all gold and silver jewellery, coins, or bars held for one year. The calculator uses live PMEX rates to value these automatically.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 4, name: 'Add business assets and receivables', text: 'Include business inventory at current market value, trade receivables you expect to collect, and investments in stocks or mutual funds at today\'s market value.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 5, name: 'Deduct liabilities', text: 'Subtract any short-term debts due within the year — outstanding loans, unpaid invoices, or other financial obligations.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 6, name: 'Review your Zakat amount', text: 'If your net zakatable wealth exceeds the Nisab and has been held for one lunar year, Zakat is 2.5% of the total. The calculator displays the exact amount in PKR.' },
    ],
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'FAQPage',
    mainEntity: [
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'What is the Zakat Nisab in Pakistan for 2026?',
        acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Zakat Nisab is the minimum wealth threshold above which Zakat becomes obligatory. In 2026, the Gold Nisab is 87.48 grams of 24K gold (approximately PKR 3.6-3.9 million at current rates). The Silver Nisab is 612.36 grams of silver (approximately PKR 390,000-420,000 at current rates). Most Pakistani scholars recommend using the Silver Nisab as it includes more Muslims in the obligation.' },
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'Which Nisab should I use — Gold or Silver?',
        acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Hanafi school (followed by most Pakistani Muslims) traditionally uses the Silver Nisab because it is lower and includes more wealth-holders in the Zakat obligation, directing more charity to the poor. Some scholars use the Gold Nisab, which results in fewer people paying Zakat. For practical purposes in Pakistan, Silver Nisab is the standard recommendation. Consult your scholar for a personal ruling.' },
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'How is Zakat calculated on gold in Pakistan?',
        acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Zakat on gold is 2.5% of the market value of all gold you have held for one lunar year (hawl). If your total gold exceeds the nisab (87.48g for Gold Nisab, or any amount if your total wealth including gold exceeds the Silver Nisab), you owe 2.5% of its current PKR market value. Use the calculator above with today\'s live 24K gold rates sourced from PMEX.' },
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'Is Zakat due on Provident Fund and pension savings?',
        acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Scholars differ on this. The common view in Pakistan is that Zakat is due on the vested (accessible) portion of your Provident Fund — the amount you can withdraw. The employer contribution that you cannot yet access may be excluded. For pension funds, Zakat is typically calculated on the lump sum when it becomes accessible. Consult your Islamic finance scholar for a ruling specific to your fund type.' },
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'When is Zakat due and how is the lunar year calculated?',
        acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Zakat is due once per Islamic lunar year (hawl). You pick a date — typically Ramadan 1 — and check your total net zakatable assets on that date each year. If your wealth has been above Nisab for the entire past lunar year on that date, Zakat is obligatory. Many Pakistanis pay Zakat in Ramadan for the spiritual blessing, though it can be paid any time after one year of ownership.' },
      },
    ],
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-10">

    <!-- Breadcrumb -->
    <nav class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-6">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-green-700">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-1">/</span>
      <a href="/tools" class="hover:text-green-700">Tools</a>
      <span class="mx-1">/</span>
      <span>Zakat Calculator</span>
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">{title}</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6 text-sm">
      Calculate your annual Zakat obligation using live gold and silver prices.
      Supports both Silver Nisab (612.36g) and Gold Nisab (87.48g) bases.
    </p>

    <ZakatCalculator client:load />

    <div class="mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg text-xs text-amber-800">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This calculator provides an estimate based on standard
      Islamic jurisprudence (Hanafi school). Zakat rules may vary by madhab and personal
      circumstances. Consult your scholar or a qualified Islamic finance expert for your
      specific situation. HisaabKar.pk is an independent information service and does not provide
      religious rulings.
    </div>

    <!-- SEO / FAQ content -->
    <div class="mt-12 prose prose-sm max-w-none text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">About Zakat in Pakistan</h2>
      <p>Zakat is one of the Five Pillars of Islam — a mandatory annual charity of <strong>2.5%</strong> on wealth held above the Nisab threshold for one full lunar year. In Pakistan, Zakat is a deeply observed religious obligation and an important mechanism for wealth redistribution to the poor.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-white mt-5 mb-2">What is the Zakat Nisab in Pakistan for 2026?</h3>
      <p>Gold Nisab: 87.48 grams of 24K gold (~PKR 3.7–4M at current rates). Silver Nisab: 612.36 grams (~PKR 390,000–420,000). Most Pakistani scholars recommend Silver Nisab as it includes more Muslims in the obligation.</p>

      <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-white mt-5 mb-2">Gold Nisab or Silver Nisab — which should I use?</h3>
      <p>The Hanafi school (followed by most Pakistanis) recommends Silver Nisab because it is lower and ensures more wealth is distributed as charity. Use Gold Nisab only if your scholar specifically advises it.</p>

      <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-white mt-5 mb-2">How is Zakat calculated on gold?</h3>
      <p>If your total gold exceeds the Nisab, you owe 2.5% of its current market value. For example: 100g of gold at PKR 41,975/gram = PKR 4,197,500 in value → Zakat = PKR 104,938.</p>

      <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-white mt-5 mb-2">Is Zakat due on Provident Fund?</h3>
      <p>Zakat is typically due on the vested (accessible) portion of your PF — the amount you could withdraw today. The employer's non-vested contribution is usually excluded. Consult your scholar for your fund type.</p>

      <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-white mt-5 mb-2">When is Zakat due?</h3>
      <p>Once per Islamic lunar year (hawl). If your wealth has been above Nisab for the entire past year on your chosen date, Zakat is obligatory. Most Pakistanis calculate and pay in Ramadan.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
